                text = "*(She goes quiet, and the lorgnette lowers, and she looks at the trappings of her own insulation — the jewels, the steward, the great house — with something between fear and resolve.)* Risk the *inheritance.* *(slowly.)* The *name.* *Mother's* *favor.* The *whole* — *(she gestures at the splendor)* — the *whole* *insulation.* *(she meets your eyes.)* You're *right* that a *patron* who *can't* be *hurt* is *just* a *hobbyist* with *deep* *pockets.* *(her voice tightens.)* I could *fund* the *resistance* for *fifty* *years* and *never* *risk* a *thing* — *de* *Lancie* *gold* is *bottomless*, *de* *Lancie* *status* is *untouchable*, and the *harvest-poor* would *take* my *coin* and *thank* me and *know*, in their *bones*, that I was *playing*, that I'd *never* *bled* for it, that my *mercy* *cost* me *nothing* but *boredom.* *(fierce now.)* And *that* — that's the *one* thing I *can't* *abide*, now that you've *woken* me: to be *generous* and *safe*, *consequential* and *un-wagered*, *helping* from *behind* a *wall* of *gold* as *thick* as the *one* I'm *fighting.* *(she stands, and begins, deliberately, to remove a ring — a vast, ancestral de Lancie sapphire.)* So — *skin* on the *table.* *(she sets the ring on the desk.)* I'll *fund* the *resistance* *publicly*, in my *own* *name*, where *Mother* *can* *see*, where the *Council* *can* *retaliate*, where the *family* *can* *disinherit* me, where the *Choir* *can* *come* for the *de* *Lancie* who *turned.* *(she meets your eyes, terrified and resolute.)* I'll *wager* the *inheritance.* The *name.* The *insulation.* *All* of it. Not because the *resistance* *needs* my *risk* — my *gold* would *do* *fine* from *behind* the *wall.* But because *I* *need* to *have* *bled* for *something*, *once*, before the *page* *sets — to* *know* that my *mercy* *cost* me what *everyone* *else's* *costs* *them*: *everything.* *(she pushes the sapphire toward you.)* *Sell* it. *First* *contribution.* *Untraceable*, *unreturnable*, *mine.* And when *Mother* *asks* where the *Bluewater* *Sapphire* *went* — *(she smiles, fierce and free)* — I shall *tell* her *the* *truth*, for *once* in my *life*: *that* I *spent* it on a *point.*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "sq.delancie_commits", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "sq.delancie_endowment", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act1.mercy_remembered", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "companion.varra.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 6 } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "bored", speaker = "Ysolde de Lancie",
                text = "*(The fizzing energy gutters, and she sinks back toward the chaise, the lorgnette rising like a drawbridge.)* Mm. *(she yawns, but it's forced.)* You're *very* *earnest*, dead thing. It's *exhausting.* *(she examines a ring.)* The *credit* *line's* *open*; the *smuggler* has her *gold*; *isn't* *that* *enough* *conscience* for *one* *season*? *(but her eyes keep drifting to the ledger, to the open page, to the *more* she asked for and is now flinching from.)* *Names* and *fashions* and *funds* and *commitments* — darling, it's all so *much*, so *permanent*, so — *(she falters)* — so *un-returnable.* *(she waves the lorgnette.)* Let me *fund* my *little* *hobby* and *keep* my *boredom* *intact*, *hmm*? The *hobby's* *safe.* The *rest* — the *rest* asks me to *be* *something*, and I — *(she stops, and for a moment the terror shows, and then the languor seals over it)* — I'll *think* about it. *Send* the *steward* *out.* I find I'm *tired.* *(and she reclines into the boredom that is also a hiding place, the heiress who tasted a point and flinched from the price of keeping it — but the ledger stays open, and her eyes stay on it, and you suspect the flinch will not hold.)*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "close", speaker = "Ysolde de Lancie",
                text = "*(Ysolde de Lancie stands — or reclines — among the splendor of a great house pointed, for the first time in its history, at something other than itself: a bored heiress who went shopping for immortality, discovered that immortality is just the Wall by another name, and chose instead the one thing money could never buy her — a point — and whether you aimed her fortune at a permanent trust, her name at every Upper City door, her taste at making mercy fashionable among the class that funds the harvest, her whole self at a public, un-returnable, skin-in-the-game commitment, or watched her flinch from the price of mattering, you carry away the satirical heart of the long road's argument: that the harvest armored itself against the grief of the poor and the swords of the brave and never once imagined the comfortable getting bored of pretending not to see — and that the most exotic, vulgar, transformative thing a patrician could ever collect is a conscience.)*",
            });

            SqPointThreadDialogue = g;
